open','','occupational-health-services','','','2015-04-22 14:55:18','2015-04-22 12:55:18','',213,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/?page_id=254',0,'page','',0),(255,1,'2015-04-21 15:59:30','2015-04-21 13:59:30','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Occupational Medical and Screening</strong>\r\n\r\nOur Occupational Medical and Screening Service was launched in July 2012.\r\n\r\nOur service includes the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Medicals for Construction Employees (Working at heights)</li>\r\n	<li>Mobile Plant and Forklift Operators</li>\r\n	<li>Screening of Food Handlers</li>\r\n	<li>Health Risk Assessments</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll medicals will be reviewed by our Consulting Occupational Health Medical Practitioner, Dr. GA Lucas.\r\n\r\n<strong>Occupational Health Practitioners are registered with:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Health Professions Council of South Africa</li>\r\n	<li>South African Nursing Council</li>\r\n	<li>The South African Society of Occupational Health Nursing Practitioners</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Occupational Health Services','','inherit','open','open','','254-revision-v1','','','2015-04-21 15:59:30','2015-04-21 13:59:30','',254,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/254-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(256,1,'2015-04-21 16:03:21','2015-04-21 14:03:21','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]Health &amp; Safety Training forms an integral part of our Integrated SHE Management System. All training courses are aligned to the skills Development Legislation and National Unit Standards.\r\n\r\nWe have developed 9 courses namely:[/vc_column_text][accordion opened=\"false\"][accordion_item title=\"Health &amp; Safety Induction\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction</li>\r\n	<li>The Reasons Incidents Occur</li>\r\n	<li>Legal Requirements</li>\r\n	<li>Organisations Rules and Procedures</li>\r\n	<li>Accident/Incident</li>\r\n	<li>Emergency Procedure</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To provide the learner with the basic knowledge of Health &amp; Safety at the workplace.</li>\r\n	<li>To comply with Section 8 and 13. To provide the learner an overview of the Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act and Relevant Sections.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Employees</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Health &amp; Safety Representative Training Programme\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction to the Incident Sequence, Legislation Sections 8, 9, 13, 14 and 37</li>\r\n	<li>Incident causes and possible consequences, Health &amp; Safety Representatives</li>\r\n	<li>Consultations, Designations and Functions, Health &amp; Safety Inspection Criteria and Practical Exercise</li>\r\n	<li>Introduction to Incident Investigation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To adhere with Sections 17-20 and ensuring a safe and healthy working environment.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure elected Health &amp; Safety Representatives conduct Health &amp; Safety Inspections of the workplace by using an appropriate check list.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure that Health &amp; Safety Committees meet to discuss the findings of the Health &amp; Safety requirements and make recommendations to the employer representatives.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure that employer institutes corrective action to prevent the re-occurrence of downgrading incidents.</li>\r\n	<li>To report incidents directly to Department of Labour should the employer not take corrective action.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Elected and Nominated Health &amp; Safety Reps</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act 85/1993 (A Management Overview)\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Relevant Definitions</li>\r\n	<li>Employer Duties  Section (8)</li>\r\n	<li>Appointments</li>\r\n	<li>Personal and Vicarious Liability</li>\r\n	<li>Applicable Regulations &amp; Occupational Health &amp; Safety Policy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To ensure that Management and persons responsible for legal compliance are informed about their duties in relationship to the requirements of the Act.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure that no Contravention Notice is issued for No-Compliance to Health &amp; Safety Legislation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Management &amp; Supervisory Staff</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Incident Investigation\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction and General Responsibilities.</li>\r\n	<li>Accident Incident Investigation, Initial Action, Analysing Accident/Incident Causes, The written report, Developing Corrective actions, Communication.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To ensure compliance with the legal requirements as per relevant legislation and ensuring preventative action is implemented to prevent re-occurrence.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure a process of reported incident to be assessed and where necessary investigated to determine the root causes of the incident.</li>\r\n	<li>To provide a process for the monitoring of planned corrective actions to prevent or reduce the risk of re-occurrence of reported incidents.\r\nWork related injuries and illnesses.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All SHE Reps &amp; Management Staff</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"First Aid Level One\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>General Information\r\n</strong>Prevention, Infection, Emergency Call, Psychological Support, Emergency Scene Management.<strong>\r\n</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Vital Signs</strong>\r\nFainting, Unconsciousness, Recovery Position, Respiratory Conditions, Choking, Drowning, Artificial Respiration, Circulatory Conditions, CPR, Acute Illness, Heart Attack, Stroke, Bronchial Asthma, Epilepsy.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Wounds &amp; Bleeding</strong>\r\nBandaging Techniques, Hypovolaemic Shock, Foreign Object Management, Amputation Injuries.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Fractures</strong>\r\nBurns, Scalds and Electrical Injuries, Poisoning/Corrosion, Inhalation, Swallowing, Injection.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The purpose of the course is to train learners to give emergency help to an injured or suddenly ill person using available material.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure compliance to General Safety Regulation 3.</li>\r\n	<li>To give emergency help and record all incidents in the workplace.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>2 Days</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Relevant First Aiders</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Basic Fire Fighting\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n\r\nFire theory, Classification of fires, Fire prevention and immediate action, Operating basic fire fighting equipment, Extinguishing fires.\r\n\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To have sufficiently trained fire fighters in all areas.</li>\r\n	<li>Identify fire risk.</li>\r\n	<li>Assist with precaution measures.</li>\r\n	<li>Identify the different types of fire extinguishers and their usage.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Designated Fire Fighters</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Emergency Coordinators Workshop\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction</li>\r\n	<li>Emergency Planning, Communications and Control</li>\r\n	<li>Bomb Threats</li>\r\n	<li>Medical Preparedness</li>\r\n	<li>Symbolic Signage</li>\r\n	<li>Basic Fire Fighting Techniques</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To provide learners with the knowledge of how to respond during an evacuation.</li>\r\n	<li>To comply to Environmental Regulations for Workplaces 9 and the relevant Fire- and Bylaws.</li>\r\n	<li>To have designated persons taking charge during an evacuation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>2 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Designated Emergency Coordinators\r\nAssistant and Evacuation Marshalls</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Asbestos Training\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n\r\nDefinitions, What is Asbestos, Where is it found, What are the dangers, Health effects, What are the legal requirements.\r\n\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The purpose of this training is to provide guidance to all persons/employees who are responsible for or concerned with the control and prevention of exposure to asbestos in the working environment.</li>\r\n	<li>The purpose of this training is to provide guidance to all persons/employees who are responsible for or concerned with the control and prevention of exposure to asbestos in the working environment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Employees</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"COIDA Workshop\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n\r\nTo inform learner to complete the relevant forms for an incident at work.\r\n\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 