ds/2015/04/lcan9.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(353,1,'2015-04-22 14:31:29','2015-04-22 12:31:29','','lcan10','','inherit','open','open','','lcan10','','','2015-04-22 14:31:29','2015-04-22 12:31:29','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/lcan10.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(354,1,'2015-04-22 14:32:27','2015-04-22 12:32:27','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]The Audit will be in compliance with the Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act 85 of 1993, the Compensation for Occupational Injuries and Diseases Act 130, the Community Fire Safety By-Law 11527 and the National Building Regulation SANS:10400 and OHSAS 18001.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Audit Includes:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Physical verification of compliance.</li>\r\n	<li>Perusal of all documentation required by law.</li>\r\n	<li>Interviews with key staff members.</li>\r\n	<li>Preparation of documentation, including audit protocol and executive summary.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>The Audit Team</strong>\r\n\r\nAll our Audit Team Members have more than 20 years experience in Fire Risk Assessment, Legal Compliance Audits at Corporate and Government Facilities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Health &amp; Safety Legal Compliance Audit</strong>\r\n\r\nSection 8(1) of the Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act (Act 85 of 1993), stipulates that the employer shall provide and maintain, as far as reasonable, a working environment that is safe and without risk to the health of the employees.\r\n\r\nBy implication, management must devise a system to ensure that the workplace is free of anything that may cause injury, damage or disease. Where this is not possible, management must inform employees about the hazards or potential hazards they may encounter and what precautionary measures must be taken to protect themselves. Management is also required to enforce these precautionary measures in the interest of health and safety.\r\n\r\nIt is noted, however, that management is not expected to take sole responsibility for health and safety. The Act is based on the principle that hazards at the workplace must be addressed through communication and cooperation between employers and their employees. Management and employees share the responsibility for proactively identifying hazards and developing control measures to make the workplace as safe and healthy as possible. In this way the employer and his employees are involved in a system whereby the Health &amp; Safety Representative may inspect the workplace regularly and then report to the Health &amp; Safety Committee, which in turn may make recommendations to the Employer.\r\n\r\nDuring recent audits it was noted that employers start with a SHE Management System, but failed to maintain it.\r\n\r\nEmbarking on a SHE Legal Compliance Audit is an important proactive tool to maintaining a controlled environment. The SHE Audit must verify the current system used by the employer and review results from previous audits.\r\n\r\nThe audit must be in line with the Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act 85 of 1993, Compensation for Occupational Injuries and Diseases Act 130, SANS 10400 Building Regulation and Community Fire Safety By-Law.\r\n\r\n<strong>Advantages of a Health &amp; Safety Audit</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Management will receive an executive summary.</li>\r\n	<li>Reduction in accidents and also creating a Health &amp; Safety Culture.</li>\r\n	<li>Compliance to all relevant Health &amp; Safety Legislation, especially Section 8: Duties of the Employer.</li>\r\n	<li>Audit team with more than 20 years experience in SHE Systems and Fire Assessments.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][rev_slider_vc alias=\"LCA\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Legal Compliance Audits','','inherit','open','open','','229-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 14:32:27','2015-04-22 12:32:27','',229,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/229-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(355,1,'2015-04-22 14:53:15','2015-04-22 12:53:15','','OHS_1','','inherit','open','open','','ohs_1','','','2015-04-22 14:53:15','2015-04-22 12:53:15','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/OHS_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(356,1,'2015-04-22 14:54:07','2015-04-22 12:54:07','','OHS_2','','inherit','open','open','','ohs_2','','','2015-04-22 14:54:07','2015-04-22 12:54:07','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/OHS_2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(357,1,'2015-04-22 14:54:14','2015-04-22 12:54:14','','OHS_3','','inherit','open','open','','ohs_3','','','2015-04-22 14:54:14','2015-04-22 12:54:14','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/OHS_3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(358,1,'2015-04-22 14:55:18','2015-04-22 12:55:18','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Occupational Medical and Screening</strong>\r\n\r\nOur Occupational Medical and Screening Service was launched in July 2012.\r\n\r\nOur service includes the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Medicals for Construction Employees (Working at heights)</li>\r\n	<li>Mobile Plant and Forklift Operators</li>\r\n	<li>Screening of Food Handlers</li>\r\n	<li>Health Risk Assessments</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll medicals will be reviewed by our Consulting Occupational Health Medical Practitioner, Dr. GA Lucas.\r\n\r\n<strong>Occupational Health Practitioners are registered with:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Health Professions Council of South Africa</li>\r\n	<li>South African Nursing Council</li>\r\n	<li>The South African Society of Occupational Health Nursing Practitioners</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][rev_slider_vc alias=\"OHS\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Occupational Health Services','','inherit','open','open','','254-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 14:55:18','2015-04-22 12:55:18','',254,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/254-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(359,1,'2015-04-22 15:00:29','2015-04-22 13:00:29','','training_1','','inherit','open','open','','training_1','','','2015-04-22 15:00:29','2015-04-22 13:00:29','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/training_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(360,1,'2015-04-22 15:00:36','2015-04-22 13:00:36','','training_3','','inherit','open','open','','training_3','','','2015-04-22 15:00:36','2015-04-22 13:00:36','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/training_3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(361,1,'2015-04-22 15:00:37','2015-04-22 13:00:37','','training_4','','inherit','open','open','','training_4','','','2015-04-22 15:00:37','2015-04-22 13:00:37','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/training_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(362,1,'2015-04-22 15:00:38','2015-04-22 13:00:38','','training_5','','inherit','open','open','','training_5','','','2015-04-22 15:00:38','2015-04-22 13:00:38','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/training_5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(363,1,'2015-04-22 15:00:39','2015-04-22 13:00:39','','training_2','','inherit','open','open','','training_2','','','2015-04-22 15:00:39','2015-04-22 13:00:39','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/training_2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(364,1,'2015-04-22 15:02:15','2015-04-22 13:02:15','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]Health &amp; Safety Training forms an integral part of our Integrated SHE Management System. All training courses are aligned to the skills Development Legislation and National Unit Standards.\r\n\r\nWe have developed 9 courses namely:[/vc_column_text][accordion opened=\"false\"][accordion_item title=\"Health &amp; Safety Induction\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction</li>\r\n	<li>The Reasons Incidents Occur</li>\r\n	<li>Legal Requirements</li>\r\n	<li>Organisations Rules and Procedures</li>\r\n	<li>Accident/Incident</li>\r\n	<li>Emergency Procedure</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To provide the learner with the basic knowledge of Health &amp; Safety at the workplace.</li>\r\n	<li>To comply with Section 8 and 13. To provide the learner an overview of the Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act and Relevant Sections.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Employees</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Health &amp; Safety Representative Training Programme\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction to the Incident Sequence, Legislation Sections 8, 9, 13, 14 and 37</li>\r\n	<li>Incident causes and possible consequences, Health &amp; Safety Representatives</li>\r\n	<li>Consultations, Designations and Functions, Health &amp; Safety Inspection Criteria and Practical Exercise</li>\r\n	<li>Introduction to Incident Investigation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To adhere with Sections 17-20 and ensuring a safe and healthy working environment.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure elected Health &amp; Safety Representatives conduct Health &amp; Safety Inspections of the workplace by using an appropriate check list.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure that Health &amp; Safety Committees meet to discuss the findings of the Health &amp; Safety requirements and make recommendations to the employer representatives.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure that employer institutes corrective action to prevent the re-occurrence of downgrading incidents.</li>\r\n	<li>To report incidents directly to Department of Labour should the employer not take corrective action.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Elected and Nominated Health &amp; Safety Reps</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Occupational Health &amp; Safety Act 85/1993 (A Management Overview)\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Relevant Definitions</li>\r\n	<li>Employer Duties  Section (8)</li>\r\n	<li>Appointments</li>\r\n	<li>Personal and Vicarious Liability</li>\r\n	<li>Applicable Regulations &amp; Occupational Health &amp; Safety Policy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To ensure that Management and persons responsible for legal compliance are informed about their duties in relationship to the requirements of the Act.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure that no Contravention Notice is issued for No-Compliance to Health &amp; Safety Legislation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Management &amp; Supervisory Staff</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Incident Investigation\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction and General Responsibilities.</li>\r\n	<li>Accident Incident Investigation, Initial Action, Analysing Accident/Incident Causes, The written report, Developing Corrective actions, Communication.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To ensure compliance with the legal requirements as per relevant legislation and ensuring preventative action is implemented to prevent re-occurrence.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure a process of reported incident to be assessed and where necessary investigated to determine the root causes of the incident.</li>\r\n	<li>To provide a process for the monitoring of planned corrective actions to prevent or reduce the risk of re-occurrence of reported incidents.\r\nWork related injuries and illnesses.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All SHE Reps &amp; Management Staff</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"First Aid Level One\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>General Information\r\n</strong>Prevention, Infection, Emergency Call, Psychological Support, Emergency Scene Management.<strong>\r\n</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Vital Signs</strong>\r\nFainting, Unconsciousness, Recovery Position, Respiratory Conditions, Choking, Drowning, Artificial Respiration, Circulatory Conditions, CPR, Acute Illness, Heart Attack, Stroke, Bronchial Asthma, Epilepsy.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Wounds &amp; Bleeding</strong>\r\nBandaging Techniques, Hypovolaemic Shock, Foreign Object Management, Amputation Injuries.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Fractures</strong>\r\nBurns, Scalds and Electrical Injuries, Poisoning/Corrosion, Inhalation, Swallowing, Injection.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The purpose of the course is to train learners to give emergency help to an injured or suddenly ill person using available material.</li>\r\n	<li>To ensure compliance to General Safety Regulation 3.</li>\r\n	<li>To give emergency help and record all incidents in the workplace.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>2 Days</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Relevant First Aiders</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Basic Fire Fighting\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n\r\nFire theory, Classification of fires, Fire prevention and immediate action, Operating basic fire fighting equipment, Extinguishing fires.\r\n\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To have sufficiently trained fire fighters in all areas.</li>\r\n	<li>Identify fire risk.</li>\r\n	<li>Assist with precaution measures.</li>\r\n	<li>Identify the different types of fire extinguishers and their usage.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Designated Fire Fighters</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Emergency Coordinators Workshop\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Introduction</li>\r\n	<li>Emergency Planning, Communications and Control</li>\r\n	<li>Bomb Threats</li>\r\n	<li>Medical Preparedness</li>\r\n	<li>Symbolic Signage</li>\r\n	<li>Basic Fire Fighting Techniques</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To provide learners with the knowledge of how to respond during an evacuation.</li>\r\n	<li>To comply to Environmental Regulations for Workplaces 9 and the relevant Fire- and Bylaws.</li>\r\n	<li>To have designated persons taking charge during an evacuation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>2 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Designated Emergency Coordinators\r\nAssistant and Evacuation Marshalls</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"Asbestos Training\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n\r\nDefinitions, What is Asbestos, Where is it found, What are the dangers, Health effects, What are the legal requirements.\r\n\r\n<strong>Objectives</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The purpose of this training is to provide guidance to all persons/employees who are responsible for or concerned with the control and prevention of exposure to asbestos in the working environment.</li>\r\n	<li>The purpose of this training is to provide guidance to all persons/employees who are responsible for or concerned with the control and prevention of exposure to asbestos in the working environment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>4 Hours</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>All Employees</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][accordion_item title=\"COIDA Workshop\"][vc_column_text]<strong>Course Content</strong>\r\n\r\nTo inform learner to complete the relevant forms for an incident at work.\r\n\r\n<strong>Duration</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Target Group</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>WCA Clerk, Human Resources</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/accordion_item][/accordion][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][rev_slider_vc alias=\"TR\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Training','','inherit','open','open','','256-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 15:02:15','2015-04-22 13:02:15','',256,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/256-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(365,1,'2015-04-22 15:05:18','2015-04-22 13:05:18','','asb_cert','','inherit','open','open','','asb_cert','','','2015-04-22 15:05:18','2015-04-22 13:05:18','',265,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/asb_cert.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(366,1,'2015-04-22 15:05:32','2015-04-22 13:05:32','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]The following Procedure must be followed when working with Asbestos Related Products.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The client/owner of the premises must appoint an Approved Inspection Authority (AIA) to identify all Asbestos Related Material on site.</li>\r\n	<li>The Approved Inspection Authority to compile an Asbestos workplan and submit it to Department of Labour that will also be considered as the Notification and Approval.</li>\r\n	<li>Only Asbestos Registered Contractors must work or remove Asbestos Related Products.</li>\r\n	<li>The Approved Inspection Authority must also do Asbestos Monitoring during Asbestos work and the AIA must issue two: (1) for the Meeting (2) Asbestos Clearance Certificate at the end of the project.</li>\r\n	<li>All Asbestos Related Products need to be disposed at an approved dumping site and the safe disposal certificate to be kept on site or with the Asbestos Registered Contractor.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFrontline can apply on behalf of contractors to obtain the Asbestos Registration with Department of Labour.\r\n\r\nSee Certificate (example)\r\n\r\nContact our office for a Quotation/Proposal.\r\n\r\nDuration of Application is +- 2 Months.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][vc_single_image image=\"365\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" alignment=\"center\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Asbestos','','inherit','open','open','','265-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 15:05:32','2015-04-22 13:05:32','',265,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/265-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(367,1,'2015-04-22 15:05:54','2015-04-22 13:05:54','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_column_text]The following Procedure must be followed when working with Asbestos Related Products.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The client/owner of the premises must appoint an Approved Inspection Authority (AIA) to identify all Asbestos Related Material on site.</li>\r\n	<li>The Approved Inspection Authority to compile an Asbestos workplan and submit it to Department of Labour that will also be considered as the Notification and Approval.</li>\r\n	<li>Only Asbestos Registered Contractors must work or remove Asbestos Related Products.</li>\r\n	<li>The Approved Inspection Authority must also do Asbestos Monitoring during Asbestos work and the AIA must issue two: (1) for the Meeting (2) Asbestos Clearance Certificate at the end of the project.</li>\r\n	<li>All Asbestos Related Products need to be disposed at an approved dumping site and the safe disposal certificate to be kept on site or with the Asbestos Registered Contractor.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFrontline can apply on behalf of contractors to obtain the Asbestos Registration with Department of Labour.\r\n\r\nSee Certificate (example)\r\n\r\nContact our office for a Quotation/Proposal.\r\n\r\nDuration of Application is +- 2 Months.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][vc_single_image image=\"365\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" alignment=\"center\" img_size=\"full\"][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Asbestos','','inherit','open','open','','265-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 15:05:54','2015-04-22 13:05:54','',265,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/265-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(368,1,'2015-04-22 15:07:01','2015-04-22 13:07:01','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][heading size=\"1\" heading_class=\"style-3\"]Taking SHE Compliance to another level[/heading][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Frontline Safety, Health &amp; Environmental Consultants was founded in 2002 by Stephan Julius with more than 22 years experience in Corporate, Government and Occupational Health &amp; Safety Systems.</li>\r\n	<li>Over the past 10 years, Frontline SHE Consultants has established themselves as the Leading Construction Health &amp; Safety Consultancy.</li>\r\n	<li>During this time, Frontline SHE Consultants acted as Health &amp; Safety Agents on 2 of the most complex public projects undertaken in the region, namely;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Cape Town World Cup 2010 Soccer Stadium</li>\r\n	<li>The Khayelitsha Railway Extension Project</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Frontline is committed to Broad Black Economic Empowerment and is currently a <strong>Level 1 BBBEE Contributor</strong>.</li>\r\n	<li>Frontline clients have access to Occupational Health, Safety and Environmental Practitioners as well as our Employee Wellness/Social Worker  all regarded as experts in their respective fields (One Stop Service).</li>\r\n	<li>Through rendering a Professional, Best Practice Safety, Health &amp; Environmental Monitoring Service, our aim is to see maintained compliance on every project by adding value to current SHE Systems, empowering all role players and creating a healthy and safe environment.</li>\r\n	<li>The effective implementation of the Safety, Health &amp; Environmental (SHE) Management Systems has offered Frontline clients above average returns and results  showing rapid and sustained reduction in incident occurrence as well as financial savings on their annual assessment by the Compensation Commissioner.</li>\r\n	<li>Our SHE Continued Development Programme ensures that we are on the cutting edge of all SHE Legislation  even having published our own Occupational Health and Safety Act (Full Version) in 2011.</li>\r\n	<li>Frontline has sustained clients for more than 9 years and contribute this to our approach of adding value to the client  with a huge emphasis on maintaining relationships.</li>\r\n	<li>Our Vision is to be the benchmark for Safety, Health &amp; Environmental Monitoring in South Africa.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Profile','','inherit','open','open','','267-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 15:07:01','2015-04-22 13:07:01','',267,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/267-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(370,1,'2015-04-22 15:10:29','2015-04-22 13:10:29','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][heading size=\"1\" heading_class=\"style-3\"]Launch of the OHSA Act 85/1993[/heading][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][vc_single_image image=\"276\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"full\"][vc_column_text]In 2012 we launched our first full version of the Occupational Health and Safety Act 85/1993.\r\nCopies are available from our office.[/vc_column_text][heading size=\"1\" heading_class=\"style-3\"]The King III Report[/heading][vc_empty_space height=\"32px\"][vc_column_text]The third report on Governance in South Africa (King III) is the culmination of the recent corporate law reform process in South Africa, following the Companies Act 71 of 2008 (the new Companies Act), which is expected to become operative on 01 July 2010. The King III report will become effective on 01 March 2010 and until then, the current King II report will still apply.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that King III should be considered in its correct context, namely a code which will be based on the new Companies Act, when it is enacted. Even though King III follows the previous King II report, it is not really helpful to merely compare its contents with the previous report, which was published in March 2002.\r\n\r\nKing III entails significant implications for companies and boards of directors, with regard to, for example, directors duties; integrated sustainability reporting; shareholder remuneration policy; risk-centric internal audit; the role and function of sub-committees; the role of the lead independent director; IT governance and security; alternative dispute solution; internal training assessment of internal control; the duty to act as a responsible corporate citizen; risk management; share options and stakeholder relationships.\r\n\r\nThe philosophy of the King III Report resolves around leadership, sustainability and corporate citizenship.\r\n\r\nTogether, the new Companies Act and King III are set to promote more stringent standards of corporate governance and greater director accountability.\r\n\r\nThe new Companies Act provides for directors personal liability for losses sustained by a Company due to the failure of a director to carry out his duties with reasonable care, skill and diligence. Any failure to comply with King III will, in all likelihood, be strong evidence of a failure by the director to carry out duties with reasonable care. In the end it all boils down to the same thing. If you fail to comply with King III, how can you argue that you complied with your duties as a director?\r\n\r\nAlthough King III may not be law, it will probably end up having the same effect and require compliance as if it were enacted into legislation. It would be a brave board of directors which failed to apply King III, thereby possibly exposing its members to personal liability under the new Companies Act.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Latest Legislation','','inherit','open','open','','275-revision-v1','','','2015-04-22 15:10:29','2015-04-22 13:10:29','',275,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/275-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(371,1,'2015-04-22 15:14:23','2015-04-22 13:14:23','','team_4','','inherit','open','open','','team_4','','','2015-04-22 15:14:23','2015-04-22 13:14:23','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/team_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(372,1,'2015-04-22 15:14:24','2015-04-22 13:14:24','','team_5','','inherit','open','open','','team_5','','','2015-04-22 15:14:24','2015-04-22 13:14:24','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/team_5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(373,1,'2015-04-22 15:14:25','2015-04-22 13:14:25','','team_1','','inherit','open','open','','team_1','','','2015-04-22 15:14:25','2015-04-22 13:14:25','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/team_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(374,1,'2015-04-22 15:14:26','2015-04-22 13:14:26','','team_2','','inherit','open','open','','team_2','','','2015-04-22 15:14:26','2015-04-22 13:14:26','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/team_2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(375,1,'2015-04-22 15:14:27','2015-04-22 13:14:27','','team_3','','inherit','open','open','','team_3','','','2015-04-22 15:14:27','2015-04-22 13:14:27','',0,'http://192.168.1.11/FRONTLINE/website/htdocs/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/team_3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(376,1,'2015-04-22 15:17:17','2015-04-22 13:17:17','[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][heading size=\"1\" heading_class=\"style-3\"]Meet the Team[/heading][vc_column_text]The Frontline Team comprises of a group o